    <text id="R13668840T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>General Ulysses S. Grant writes Henry Halleck in May, 1864, to ask that General
                    Franz Sigel be sent to Staunton to destroy the road there, and prevent the flow
                    of more Confederate supplies from the town.</p>
            </div1> 
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    HDQRS. ARMIES OF THE UNITED STATES,
                    <name type="recipient">Maj.-Gen. HALLECK:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1864-05-17">May 17, 1864. (Received 3.45 p. m.)</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute/>
                </opener>
                <p>Cannot Gen. Sigel go up Shenandoah Valley to Staunton? The enemy is evidently
                    drawing supplies largely from that source, and if Sigel can destroy the road
                    there, it will be of vast importance to us. The weather is still cloudy and
                    threatening, as if the rain was not yet over.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute/>
                    <signed>U. S. GRANT,<lb/> Lieut.-Gen., U. S. Army.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
